In `/packages/do/src/rpc/index.ts` lines 150-159, the BatchedRpcExecutor's timer-based flush could create floating promises:

```typescript
execute(method: string, params: Record<string, unknown>): Promise<unknown> {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    this.queue.push({ method, params, resolve, reject })

    if (this.queue.length >= this.options.maxBatchSize) {
      this.flush()  // <-- No await, floating promise
    } else if (!this.flushTimer) {
      this.flushTimer = setTimeout(() => this.flush(), this.options.flushInterval)
    }
  })
}
```

The `this.flush()` call is not awaited, which means errors during batch processing won't propagate correctly in this code path.

**Recommended fix**: Handle the flush promise properly or use void operator to indicate intentional fire-and-forget.

